  "prompt": "When do the rabies symptoms occur in humans?",
  "response": "The incubation period for rabies in humans (the time between exposure and the onset of symptoms) is highly variable, but it's typically **between 3 and 12 weeks.** However, it can range from **less than a week to over a year, and in very rare cases, even longer.**\n\nSeveral factors influence the length of the incubation period:\n\n*   **Location of the bite:** Bites closer to the brain (e.g., on the face, head, or neck) generally have shorter incubation periods because the virus has a shorter distance to travel to reach the central nervous system.\n*   **Severity of the bite:** More severe bites, especially those with deep wounds or multiple bites, may lead to shorter incubation periods.\n*   **Amount of virus introduced:** A higher viral load in the saliva of the infected animal can shorten the incubation period.\n*   **Age of the person:** Children tend to have shorter incubation periods than adults, possibly due to their developing nervous systems.\n*   **Immune status of the person:** Individuals with compromised immune systems may have longer or shorter incubation periods, depending on the nature of their immune deficiency.\n*   **Strain of the rabies virus:** Different strains of the rabies virus may have different incubation periods.\n\n**Once symptoms appear, rabies is almost always fatal.**  This is why prompt post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) is crucial after any potential exposure to rabies.\n\n**Stages of Rabies Symptoms**\n\nRabies symptoms typically progress through several stages:\n\n1.  **Prodromal phase:** This initial phase lasts 2-10 days and involves non-specific symptoms like:\n\n    *   Fever\n    *   Headache\n    *   Malaise (general feeling of discomfort or illness)\n    *   Fatigue\n    *   Loss of appetite\n    *   Nausea and vomiting\n    *   Pain or itching at the site of the bite (even if it has healed)\n\n2.  **Acute Neurologic Phase:** This phase marks the onset of neurological symptoms and can manifest in two main forms:\n\n    *   **Furious (encephalitic) rabies:** This is the more common form (about 80% of cases) and is characterized by:\n\n        *   Agitation, anxiety, and irritability\n        *   Hyperactivity\n        *   Insomnia\n        *   Confusion\n        *   Hallucinations\n        *   Seizures\n        *   Hydrophobia (fear of water) - spasms of the throat muscles when attempting to swallow liquids\n        *   Aerophobia (fear of drafts or fresh air)\n    *   **Paralytic (dumb) rabies:** This form is less common and is characterized by:\n\n        *   Gradual paralysis, usually starting at the site of the bite and spreading upwards.\n        *   Weakness\n        *   Loss of sensation\n        *   Absence of hydrophobia or hyperactivity.\n\n3.  **Coma:** Regardless of the form of rabies, the disease eventually progresses to a coma.\n\n4.  **Death:** Death usually occurs within days or weeks after the onset of neurological symptoms, typically due to respiratory failure.\n\n**Important Note:**  If you suspect you have been exposed to rabies (e.g., bitten or scratched by a potentially rabid animal), seek immediate medical attention.  Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP), which includes a series of rabies vaccine and rabies immunoglobulin shots, is highly effective in preventing the disease if administered promptly after exposure.  Do not wait for symptoms to appear, as PEP is only effective before symptoms develop.\n",
